title: For Sale:  Daewoo DR-200 (K2) 5.56mm w/ ACE folding stock
postcontent:
This is one for the hipsters. If you want a rifle that'll run AR-15 mags, is lighter and handier than most AR-15s (and certainly lighter than gas-piston AR-15s), and just as accurate, look no further. It's what happens when Korea says, "Re don't rike your M16 Amelica, so re made something better!". Enter the K2, or as Kimber imports it, the DR200. This one has a Sturmwerkz stock adapter/folding mechanism and relatively short (7") ACE stock. I got it short because I'm usually wearing heavy clothing when I shoot. 

Round count: Just over 300 total rounds--we can call it 350 if you want. The previous owner fired a single magazine through it. 
The receiver says ".223" but the barrel is chambered in 5.56mm NATO with a 1:12 twist (meaning stick to the 55gr bullets). I've shot .223 stuff through it and haven't noticed a difference in groups between the two standards. The rifle shoots straight at 200 yards, haven't tried anything further. It's actually wonderfully accurate and of all the rifles I've ever owned it was by far the easiest to zero. 

Rifle is in excellent condition. I can also offer the Magpul MOE collapsible stock and stock adapter that it came with. Both are set up for optimal cheek weld. Ask about magazines, scopes, etc! I have a Millet DMS-1 on a PEPR mount that's still zeroed to it if you're interested.

Trades: 
Vz58 clones
CZ pistols 
+ cash

I'd prefer not to ship (my FFL is very affordable but unreliable and ships stuff at his leisure), but can if you don't come off as a scumbag.

I made a new stock for it. Not the best stock, but it works just fine for a 22lr. This allows you to pack it in a smaller area and leave the scope on it all the time. Let's face it, the selling feature of the original stock is that it floats, but if your pack falls in the water and sinks, so does the gun. 

I'm asking $325 for it. The buyer pays the shipping and transfer fees, unless we do a trade. 

Anyway, if you are not familiar with this gun, here is the info from Henry's website:

U.S. Survival AR-7 Rifle
Don’t Leave Civilization Without One

Since 1959 the venerable AR-7 has been the choice of U.S. Air Force pilots who need a small-caliber rifle they can count on should they have to punch out over a remote area. Through the years the AR-7’s reputation for portability, ease of operation and reliability has carried over to the civilian world. Today it’s a favorite of bush pilots, backpackers and backcountry adventurers who, like their Air Force counterparts, need a rifle that’s easy to carry yet has the accuracy to reliably take down small game.

Like the original Henry U.S. Survival Rifle, this innovative, semi-automatic model is lightweight (3.5 lbs.) and highly portable. At just 16.5″ long, when all the components are stowed, it easily fits into the cargo area of a plane, boat or in a backpack. It’s chambered in .22 LR so you can carry a large quantity of ammunition without adding much weight to your gear.

When disassembled the pieces fit inside the impact-resistant, water resistant stock. Assembly is as easy as attaching the receiver to the stock, inserting the barrel, and screwing on the nut. In a few seconds, without any tools, the Henry U.S. Survival AR-7 is ready for action. It comes standard with a sturdy steel barrel covered in tough ABS plastic that’s coated with Teflon™ for complete protection against corrosion. It’s engineered for perfect balance and the ability to maintain its tack-driving accuracy, even after thousands of rounds.

The receiver is also coated with Teflon™ for superior weatherproofing and waterproof protection, even in harsh saltwater environments. The updated receiver is grooved, making it easy to top off with your favorite optics.

The Henry U.S. Survival AR-7 is available in two finishes; Black and Mossy Oak Break-Up Camo Pattern.  All models are equipped with an adjustable rear sight and a blade front sight.

title: For Sale:  Stevens 16-ga single barrel, hammer-fired, break open shotgun (pre-'68)
postcontent:
Presenting a very scarce Stevens 16 gauge single barrel shotgun. This hammer-fired, breach loader has a model number (940A) not found in gun books and a hunting dog scene engraved on the right of the receiver. The shotgun is pre-1968 manufacture due to no external serial number present. There may be one on the receiver tang, under the stock -not sure. Break-open lever is on right side of receiver and the barrel is 28" long, with a 2 3/4" chamber.

Stevens Arms became a division of Savage Arms Corporation (Westfield, MA) around 1920... with the break-open lever on the side -versus the tang- of the receiver dates it probably from the 1940's-50's. While in functional condition, the nice, even patina would make it a cool fireplace mantle gun!

The shotgun also comes with 1 soft case (Allen brand).

HSGI Bungee straps can be adjusted when installed, and provide a single bungee pull tab release for 2 x M4 magazines or 1 x M14 or AK type magazine. 

The WASATCH plate carrier was designed specifically for 19th SFG, whose operators needed a modular system to wear over their issue Interceptor body armor. The WASATCH can be worn over overt or covert soft armor, or as a stand-alone plate system. The front and back carriers will hold any 10"x12" flat or multi-curve plate on the market today. The rear carrier also has a separate internal compartment for additional storage or a hydration pouch, although for hydration we recommend considering an external hydration carrier, because an internal hydration pouch will fluctuate in size with use, and affect the fit of the waist belt

These pockets are universal for other magazines (6 AK, 6 M14/FN, etc.), and since they are integral, you still maintain the ability to add more mission specific pouches.

The magazine pockets expose enough of the 30 rd magazines to be grasped quickly, and both front and rear magazine flaps are fully adjustable. The outer pockets can be used for a radio, handgun, smoke or flashbang grenade, etc.

The front plate-carrier bib offers further real-estate for mounting modular pouches to suit your needs. There are 4 side release buckles to offer you in-and-out access in a hurry
